THE
WASTE
LAND

T.
S
Eliot

created
an
extraordinary
interest
among
American
writers
and

critics,
when
it
originally
appeared
in
THE
DIAL
last
Novem-

ber.
This
interest
has
grown
steadily,
and
the
appearance
of

the
poem
in
book
form,
with
full
annotations
by
the
author,
is

as
much
an
event
in
the
world
of
books
as
the
original
publica-

tion
was
in
the
magazine
world.
In
view
of
this,
THE
DIAL

has
procured
a
number
of
copies
of
the
limited
first
edition
of

The
Waste
Land
and
offers
them'
to
new
subscribers.

This
is
the
only
form
in
which
The
Waste
Land
can
now
be

procured,
as
the
November
Dial,
and
the
issue
of
The
Criterion

(London)
which
contained
the
poem,
are
both
exhausted.
The

Boni
and
Liveright
publication
is
the
first
edition
consisting
of

one
thousand
numbered
copies,
and
is
certain
to
become
a
col-

lector's
rarity
in
a
short
time.

The
Notes
which
Mr.
Eliot
has
written
give
definite
clues
to

the
framework
and
symbolism
of
the
poem
and
include
identi-

fication
of
certain
quoted
passages
which
have
puzzled
his

readers.
It
was
in
accordance
with
the
author's
wishes
that
the

poem
was
originally
published
without
the
Notes;
but
readers

will
be
glad
to
have
the
unique
pleasure
of
reading
a
poet's

annotations
on
himself.

The
number
of
copies
The
Dial
has
been
able
to
procure
from

the
publishers
is
limited.
Until
the
supply
is
exhausted,
copies

of
The
Waste
Land
may
be
obtained
with
a
year's
subscription

to
THE
DIAL.
The
annual
rate
of
THE
DIAL
is
$5.00.
THE

DIAL
and
THE
WASTE
LAND
together
may
be
had
for
$5.50.
